<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 The <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> is dated 25 March.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>In a letter of 25 June 1775 that was reprinted in many newspapers, John Burgoyne wrote Lord Stanley: B<span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">oston</span> is a peninsula, joined to the main land only by a narrow Neck, which on the first troubles General Gage fortified; arms of the sea, and the harbour surround the rest on the other side, one of these arms to the north is Charlestown, or rather was, for it is now rubbish, and over it is a large hill, which is also (like Boston) a peninsula; to the south of the town is a still larger scope of ground, containing three hills, joining also to the main by a tongue of land, and called Dorchester Neck; the heights as above described, both north and south (in the soldiers phrase) command the town, that is, give an opportunity of erecting batteries above any that you can make against them, and consequently are much more advantageous (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">New England Chronicle: or, the Essex Gazette</span>, 23 Nov. 1775).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0390-0002" class="document">Inventory of British Goods Left in Boston, 20 Mar.</a>, <span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: 'printed above as ' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-12-02]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>an enclosure to <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0390-0001" class="document">GW to Hancock, 24 Mar. 1776</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0409-0002" class="document">Return of British Ordnance Stores Left in Boston, 22 Mar.</a>, printed as an enclosure to <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0409-0001" class="document">GW to Hancock, 27 Mar. 1776</a>. Gen. Edward Braddocks expeditionary force was defeated near the Monongahela River in western Pennsylvania on 9 July 1755, and a short time later orders were given to destroy the provisions and artillery stores stockpiled at Col. Thomas Dunbars camp in order to facilitate a retreat (see Anonymous Letter on Braddocks Campaign, 25 July 1755, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Stanley Pargellis, ed. &lt;i&gt;Military Affairs in North America, 17481765: Selected Documents from the Cumberland Papers in Windsor Castle&lt;/i&gt;. 1936. Reprint. Hamden, Conn., 1969. ]">Pargellis, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Military Affairs in North America</span></span>, 11224). Dunbar took command of Braddocks force after the generals death from wounds on 13 July 1755 and retreated to Philadelphia.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>For Carters desire to have his grandson Landon Carter appointed an aide-de-camp to Gen. Charles Lee, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0248&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0248-fn-0001#GEWN-03-03-02-0248-fn-0001" class="document">Carter to GW, 20 Feb. 1776, n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>John Tayloe and his family lived at Mount Airy near Sabine Hall.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0408-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>Six regiments under the command of Gen. John Sullivan marched for New York on 29 March. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0414" class="document">General Orders, 28 Mar. 1776</a>. For the return of rations drawn by the British army on 16 Mar., see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0390-0001&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0390-0001-fn-0007#GEWN-03-03-02-0390-0001-fn-0007" class="document">GW to Hancock, 24 Mar. 1776, n.7</a>.</p>

</div>
